Association with a sea anemone alters the skin microbiome of clownfish

Victoria French, Grace Beery & Madison Pacaro

March 9, 2021

Introduction

Sea anemone hosting temporarily alters clownfish skin microbiome. After analyzing the microbiome of clownfish not exposed to anemones, clownfish associated with anemones, and clownfish after being removed from their associated anemones, it was found that the microbiome of clownfish mucous is significantly different between hosting and non-hosting individuals. Interestingly, it was also found that a hosting clownfishs mucosal microbiome returns to that of a non-associated clownfish when removed from the associated anemone for a number of weeks (Pratte et al, 2018). We analyzed a subset of the data presented by Pratte et al, to gain practice with RStudio metabarcoding and to test the replicability of the authors genomic analysis. We used the DADA2 pipeline to filter and analyze Illumina raw sequence reads, to assign taxonomic classification via the SILVA v138 reference database, of anemone, clownfish and the associated water column. We utilized phyloseq to visualize this data and construct an ordinate plot based on Bray-Curtis dissimilarity to identify relatedness between sample microbiomes. We found that the microbial community was similar across analyses but lost specificity with the reduction of sample sizes in this replication. The differences found in taxonomic assignment contributed to inconclusive results when analyzing microbiome relatedness. Overall, this project was able to successfully replicate methods of the original analysis but was unable to produce the same results as were found in the original paper.

Pratte ZA, Patin NV, McWhirt ME, Caughman AM, Parris DJ, Stewart FJ (2018) Association with a sea anemone alters the skin microbiome of clownfish. Coral Reefs 37:1119-1125

Data Analysis & Methods

First we designated a path to the fastq files we will be analyzing.

path <-"C:/Users/Maddy/Documents/BI586/fishmicrobes_2021_assign1/fastqfiles"
fns <- list.files(path)
fns

To divide fastq files into matched forward and reversed lists, determined by either a _1 or _2, we first had to ensure fastq files were in the same order. We then removed the .fastq from each file name.

fastqs <- fns[grepl(".fastq$", fns)]
fastqs <- sort(fastqs)
fnFs <- fastqs[grepl("_1", fastqs)]
fnRs <- fastqs[grepl("_2", fastqs)]

sample.names <- sapply(strsplit(basename(fnFs), "_"), `[`, 1)

We then set the full path to our forward and reverse reads.

fnFs <- file.path(path, fnFs) 
fnRs <- file.path(path, fnRs)
fnFs
fnRs

Quality profiles were then plotted for forward and reverse reads to determine where to trim them.

#Forward 1-9
plotQualityProfile(fnFs[1:9])

#Forward 10-18
plotQualityProfile(fnFs[10:18])

#Reverse 1-9
plotQualityProfile(fnRs[1:9])

#Reverse 10-18
plotQualityProfile(fnRs[10:18])

We then created a new subdirectory for trimmed and filtered files.

filt_path <- file.path(path, "trimmed")
if(!file_test("-d", filt_path)) dir.create(filt_path)
filtFs <- file.path(path, "filtered", paste0(sample.names, "_F_filt.fastq.gz"))
filtRs <- file.path(path, "filtered", paste0(sample.names, "_R_filt.fastq.gz"))
names(filtFs) <- sample.names
names(filtRs) <- sample.names

To filter the reads, we set trunclen to 240 because, despite some samples falling off extremely early (around cycle 100) no samples fell below a quality score of 20 after 250 bp.

We determined that 240 maximizes the read output during inital filtering and minimizes presence of bimeras while still resulting in successful paired end merges. We excluded the filtering parameter Trimleft because our raw data did not contain primer sequences. The primer sequences used were

  • 515F (GTGYCAGCMGCCGCGGTAA)

  • 806R (GGACTACNVGGGTWTCTAAT)

for the 16S V4 region according to earth microbiome project.

out <- filterAndTrim(fnFs, filtFs, fnRs, filtRs, truncLen=240,
                     maxN=0, 
                     maxEE=1, 
                     truncQ=2, 
                     rm.phix=TRUE,
                     compress=TRUE, multithread=FALSE)

DADA2 was then utilized to employ a parametric error model to determine the error rate of the amplicon dataset. We kept the standard max consistency of 30 to increase the number of cycles and allow for convergence.

setDadaOpt(MAX_CONSIST=30)
errF <- learnErrors(filtFs, multithread=TRUE)
## 26232960 total bases in 109304 reads from 18 samples will be used for learning the error rates.
errR <- learnErrors(filtRs, multithread=TRUE)
## 26232960 total bases in 109304 reads from 18 samples will be used for learning the error rates.

We plotted the found forward and reverse errors to visually confirm our data. The black line represents the estimated error rates, and the points represent the fit of the error rates. We should see a negative linear relationship in error rates, as quality score increases.

plotErrors(errF, nominalQ=TRUE)

plotErrors(errR, nominalQ=TRUE)

Reads were dereplicated, collapsing all reads into unique sequences. Then, the dereplicated reads were assigned to sample names.

derepFs <- derepFastq(filtFs, verbose=FALSE)
derepRs <- derepFastq(filtRs, verbose=FALSE)

names(derepFs) <-sample.names
names(derepRs) <- sample.names

We used a band size of 16 to infer sequence variants as it is suggested as the default size for Illumina.

setDadaOpt(BAND_SIZE=16)
dadaFs <- dada(derepFs, err=errF, multithread=TRUE)

To determine how many real variants are within unique input sequences, we looked at the dada class objects by sample. Pooled processing for dada is available with the function pool=TRUE, which may provide better results for low sampling depths.

Paired ends from forward and reverse reads were merged to obtain the full sequences. Denoised forward reads were aligned with reverse-compliment corresponding denoised reverse reads.

mergers <- mergePairs(dadaFs, filtFs, dadaRs, filtRs, verbose=FALSE)
head(mergers[[1]])

We then constructed a sequence table. This table contains amplicon sequence variants (ASV).

seqtab <- makeSequenceTable(mergers)
dim(seqtab)
## [1]   18 1809

We then identified and removed chimeric sequences in our data.

seqtab.nochim <- removeBimeraDenovo(seqtab, method="consensus", multithread=TRUE, verbose=TRUE)
## Identified 12 bimeras out of 1809 input sequences.
dim(seqtab.nochim)
## [1]   18 1797
sum(seqtab.nochim)/sum(seqtab)
## [1] 0.9969415
#chimeras account for only about ~1% of the merged sequence reads

We created a csv file to save the full sequences and sequences with chimeras removed.

write.csv(seqtab,file="fishmicrobes_seqtab.csv")
write.csv(seqtab.nochim,file="fishmicrobes_nochim.csv")

Reference Database

Reference database used was Silva SSU taxonomic training data formatted for DADA2 (Silva version 138) as sequences were assessed by Illumina sequencing of the 16S rRNA gene (V4 region). Original analysis done on silva v119.

Citation:

@dataset{michael_r_mclaren_2020_3986799, author = {Michael R. McLaren}, title = {{Silva SSU taxonomic training data formatted for DADA2 (Silva version 138)}}, month = aug, year = 2020, note = {{These files are intended for use in classifying prokaryotic 16S sequencing data and are not appropriate for classifying eukaryotic ASVs. The new method implemented within DADA2 for constructing these files only includes 100 eukaryotic sequences for use as an outgroup.}}, publisher = {Zenodo}, version = 2, doi = {10.5281/zenodo.3986799}, url = {https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3986799}

Conclusion

Overall, our project was unable to conclusively produce the same results as originally presented in Pratte et al.We found similar taxonomic classification, yet our assignments were of broader scale and the presence of specific classes were lost entirely. This could be due to a multiple of factors related to sampling. We used a much smaller sampling size across the three sampling types (A.clarkii n=3, water column n=2, anemone n=2) when running our analyses compared to the original paper (A.clarkii n=12, water column n=9, anemone n=22). Under the assumption that every individuals microbiome is differentiated due to conditional inputs and random chance, it is likely that the response of the hosting treatment individual is not indicative of a larger population response. There is also a chance that the sequenced anemone and the sequenced hosting clownfish had zero interaction history as association between specific colonies and A.clarkii was not recorded in metadata. This could account for the differences we see in taxonomic makeup between our anemone and hosting clownfish microbiome communities. The higher order classifications led to vastly different Bray-Curtis relationships in our data than in the metadata. There are very weak clustering patterns overall with non-hosting outliers indicating the greatest differences. While the some non-hosting, hosting and post-hosting individuals maintain relative similarity to the anemone samples. Therefore we can not conclusively say that association with anemone alters the skin microbiome of a clownfish.
